@graph.rdfs:comment: The Law of Mass Action, first expressed by Waage and Guldberg in 1864 (Waage, P.; Guldberg, C. M. Forhandlinger: Videnskabs-Selskabet i Christiana 1864, 35) states that the speed of a chemical reaction is proportional to the quantity of the reacting substances. More formally, the change of a product quantity is proportional to the product of reactant activities. In the case of a reaction occurring in a gas phase, the activities are equal to the partial pressures. In the case of a well-stirred aqueous medium, the activities are equal to the concentrations. In the case of discrete kinetic description, the quantity are expressed in number of molecules and the relevant volume are implicitely embedded in the kinetic constant.
@graph.rdfs:label: mass action rate law

@graph.rdfs:comment: First general rate equation for reactions involving enzymes, it was presented in "Victor Henri. Lois Générales de l'Action des Diastases. Paris, Hermann, 1903.". The reaction is assumed to be made of a reversible of the binding of the substrate to the enzyme, followed by the breakdown of the complex generating the product. Ten years after Henri, Michaelis and Menten presented a variant of his equation, based on the hypothesis that the dissociation rate of the substrate was much larger than the rate of the product generation. Leonor Michaelis, Maud Menten (1913). Die Kinetik der Invertinwirkung, Biochem. Z. 49:333-369.
@graph.rdfs:label: Henri-Michaelis-Menten rate law

@graph.rdfs:comment: Rate-law presented in "Donald D. Van Slyke and Glenn E. Cullen. The mode of action of urease and of enzymes in general. J. Biol. Chem., Oct 1914; 19: 141-180". It assumes that the enzymatic reaction occurs as two irreversible steps.E+S -> ES -> E+P. Although of the same form than the Henri-Michaelis-Menten equation, it is semantically different since K now represents the ratio between the production rate and the association rate of the enzyme and the substrate.
@graph.rdfs:label: Van Slyke-Cullen rate law

@graph.rdfs:comment: The Briggs-Haldane rate law is a general rate equation that does not require the restriction of equilibrium of Henri-Michaelis-Menten or irreversible reactions of Van Slyke, but instead make the hypothesis that the complex enzyme-substrate is in quasi-steady-state. Although of the same form than the Henri-Michaelis-Menten equation, it is semantically different since Km now represents a pseudo-equilibrium constant, and is equal to the ratio between the rate of consumption of the complex (sum of dissociation of substrate and generation of product) and the association rate of the enzyme and the substrate.
@graph.rdfs:label: Briggs-Haldane rate law

@graph.rdfs:comment: Numerical parameter that quantifies the forward velocity of a chemical reaction. This parameter encompasses all the contributions to the velocity except the quantity of the reactants.
@graph.rdfs:label: forward rate constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Numerical parameter that quantifies the forward velocity of a chemical reaction. This parameter encompasses all the contributions to the velocity except the quantity of the reactants. It is to be used in a reaction modelled using a continuous framework.
@graph.rdfs:label: forward rate constant, continuous case

@graph.rdfs:comment: Numerical parameter that quantifies the forward velocity of a chemical reaction. This parameter encompasses all the contributions to the velocity except the quantity of the reactants. It is to be used in a reaction modelled using a discrete framework.
@graph.rdfs:label: forward rate constant, discrete case

@graph.rdfs:comment: Numerical parameter that quantifies the forward velocity of a chemical reaction. This parameter encompasses all the contributions to the velocity except the quantity of the reactants.
@graph.rdfs:label: reverse rate constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Number of different substances consumed by a chemical reaction.
@graph.rdfs:label: number of reactants

@graph.rdfs:comment: The order of a reaction with respect to a certain reactant is defined as the power to which its concentration term in the rate equation is raised.
@graph.rdfs:label: order of a reaction with respect to a reactant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Numerical parameter that quantifies the velocity of a chemical reaction where reactants have non-integral orders. This parameter encompasses all the contributions to the velocity except the quantity of the reactants.
@graph.rdfs:label: non-integral order rate constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Numerical parameter that quantifies the forward velocity of a chemical reaction where reactants have non-integral orders. This parameter encompasses all the contributions to the velocity except the quantity of the reactants.
@graph.rdfs:label: forward non-integral order rate constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Numerical parameter that quantifies the reverse velocity of a chemical reaction where products have non-integral orders. This parameter encompasses all the contributions to the velocity except the quantity of the products.
@graph.rdfs:label: reverse non-integral order rate constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Numerical parameter that quantifies the forward velocity of a chemical reaction independant of the reactant quantities. This parameter encompasses all the contributions to the velocity.
@graph.rdfs:label: forward zeroth order rate constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Reaction scheme where the products are created from the reactants and the change of a product quantity is proportional to the product of reactant activities. The reaction scheme does not include any reverse process that creates the reactants from the products. It is to be used in a reaction modelled using a continuous framework.

@graph.rdfs:comment: An event involving one or more physical entities that modifies the structure, location or free energy of at least one of the participants.
@graph.rdfs:label: biochemical or transport reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: regulation
@graph.rdfs:label: control

@graph.rdfs:comment: Negative modulation of the execution of a process.
@graph.rdfs:label: inhibition

@graph.rdfs:comment: Positive modulation of the execution of a process.
@graph.rdfs:label: stimulation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: trigger
@graph.rdfs:label: necessary stimulation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modification of the velocity of a reaction by lowering the energy of the transition state.
@graph.rdfs:label: catalysis

@graph.rdfs:comment: All the preceding events or participating entities are necessary to perform the control.
@graph.rdfs:label: and

@graph.rdfs:comment: Any of the preceding events or participating entities are necessary to perform the control.
@graph.rdfs:label: or

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: exclusive or
@graph.rdfs:label: xor

@graph.rdfs:comment: An event involving one or more chemical entities that modifies the electrochemical structure of at least one of the participants.
@graph.rdfs:label: biochemical reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: association
@graph.rdfs:label: non-covalent binding

@graph.rdfs:comment: Rupture of a covalent bond resulting in the conversion of one physical entity into several physical entities.
@graph.rdfs:label: cleavage

@graph.rdfs:comment: Complete disappearance of a physical entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: degradation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Transformation of a non-covalent complex that results in the formation of several independent biochemical entities
@graph.rdfs:label: dissociation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Biochemical reaction that does not result in the modification of covalent bonds of reactants, but rather modifies the conformation of some reactants, that is the relative position of their atoms in space.
@graph.rdfs:label: conformational transition

@graph.rdfs:comment: Biochemical reaction that results in the modification of some covalent bonds.
@graph.rdfs:label: conversion

@graph.rdfs:comment: Process through which a DNA sequence is copied to produce a complementary RNA.
@graph.rdfs:label: transcription

@graph.rdfs:comment: Process in which a polypeptide chain is produced from a messenger RNA.
@graph.rdfs:label: translation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Movement of a physical entity without modification of the structure of the entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: translocation reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: Vmax
@graph.rdfs:label: maximal velocity

@graph.rdfs:comment: Version of Henri-Michaelis-Menten equation where kp*[E]t is replaced by the maximal velocity, Vmax, reached when all the enzyme is active.
@graph.rdfs:label: Henri-Michaelis-Menten equation, Vmax form

@graph.rdfs:comment: A number of objects of the same type, identical or different, involved in a biochemical event.
@graph.rdfs:label: number of biochemical items

@graph.rdfs:comment: Number of regions on a reactant to which specific other reactants, in this context collectively called ligands, form a chemical bond.
@graph.rdfs:label: number of binding sites

@graph.rdfs:comment: Empirical parameter created by Archibald Vivian Hill to describe the cooperative binding of oxygen on hemoglobine (Hill (1910). The possible effects of the aggregation of the molecules of haemoglobin on its dissociation curves. J Physiol 40: iv-vii).
@graph.rdfs:label: Hill coefficient

@graph.rdfs:comment: Empirical constant created by Archibald Vivian Hill to describe the cooperative binding of oxygen on hemoglobine (Hill (1910). The possible effects of the aggregation of the molecules of haemoglobin on its dissociation curves. J Physiol 40: iv-vii). Different from a microscopic dissociation constant, it has the dimension of concentration to the power of the Hill coefficient.
@graph.rdfs:label: Hill constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Empirical equation created by Archibald Vivian Hill to describe the cooperative binding of oxygen on hemoglobine (Hill (1910). The possible effects of the aggregation of the molecules of haemoglobin on its dissociation curves. J Physiol 40: iv-vii).
@graph.rdfs:label: Hill-type rate law, generalised form

@graph.rdfs:comment: Constant with the dimension of a powered concentration. It is determined at half-saturation, half-activity etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: equilibrium or steady-state constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Dissociation constant equivalent to an intrinsic microscopic dissociation constant, but obtained from an averaging process, for instance by extracting the root of a Hill constant.
@graph.rdfs:label: pseudo-dissociation constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Hill equation rewritten by creating a pseudo-microscopic constant, equal to the Hill constant powered to the opposite of the Hill coefficient.
@graph.rdfs:label: Hill-type rate law, microscopic form

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: [X]
@graph.rdfs:label: concentration of an entity pool

@graph.rdfs:comment: Concentration of an object divided by the value of another parameter having the dimension of a concentration.
@graph.rdfs:label: specific concentration of an entity

@graph.rdfs:comment: Hill equation rewritten by replacing the concentration of reactant with its reduced form, that is the concentration divide by a pseudo-microscopic constant, equal to the Hill constant powered to the opposite of the Hill coefficient.
@graph.rdfs:label: Hill-type rate law, reduced form

@graph.rdfs:comment: Kinetics of enzymes that react only with one substance, their substrate. The total enzyme concentration is considered to be equal to 1, therefore the maximal velocity equals the catalytic constant.
@graph.rdfs:label: normalised enzymatic rate law for unireactant enzymes

@graph.rdfs:comment: Chemical process in which atoms have their oxidation number (oxidation state) changed.
@graph.rdfs:label: redox reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: Chemical process during which a molecular entity loses electrons.
@graph.rdfs:label: oxidation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Chemical process in which a molecular entity gain electrons.
@graph.rdfs:label: reduction

@graph.rdfs:comment: Reaction in which a reactant gives birth to two products identical to itself.
@graph.rdfs:label: duplication

@graph.rdfs:comment: Process in which a DNA duplex is transformed into two identical DNA duplexes.
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA replication

@graph.rdfs:comment: Process that involves the participation of chemical or biological entities and is composed of several elementary steps or reactions.
@graph.rdfs:label: composite biochemical process

@graph.rdfs:comment: Substance that decreases the probability of a chemical reaction, without itself being consumed or transformed by the reaction, by stericaly hindering the interaction between reactants.
@graph.rdfs:label: competitive inhibitor

@graph.rdfs:comment: Substance that decreases the probability of a chemical reaction, without itself being consumed or transformed by the reaction, and without sterically hindering the interaction between reactants.
@graph.rdfs:label: non-competitive inhibitor

@graph.rdfs:comment: Chemical reaction where a proton is given by a compound, the acid, to another one, the base (Brønsted-Lowry definition). An alternative, more general, definition is a reaction where a compound, the base, gives a pair of electrons to another, the acid (Lewis definition).
@graph.rdfs:label: acid-base reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: Ionization is the physical process of converting an atom or molecule into an ion by changing the difference between the number of protons and electrons.
@graph.rdfs:label: ionisation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Covalent reaction that results in the addition of a chemical group on a molecule.
@graph.rdfs:label: addition of a chemical group

@graph.rdfs:comment: Covalent reaction that results in the removal of a chemical group from a molecule.
@graph.rdfs:label: removal of a chemical group

@graph.rdfs:comment: Addition of a proton (H+) to a chemical entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: protonation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Removal of a proton (hydrogen ion H+) from a chemical entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: deprotonation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Addition of a methyl group (-CH3) to a chemical entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: methylation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Addition of an acetyl group (-COCH3) to a chemical entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: acetylation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Addition of a phosphate group (-H2PO4) to a  chemical entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: phosphorylation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Addition of a saccharide group to a chemical entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: glycosylation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Addition of a palmitoyl group (CH3-[CH2]14-CO-) to a chemical entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: palmitoylation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Addition of a myristoyl (CH3-[CH2]12-CO-) to a chemical entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: myristoylation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: sulphation
@graph.rdfs:label: sulfation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: isoprenylation
@graph.rdfs:label: prenylation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Addition of a farnesyl group (CH2-CH=C(CH3)-CH2-CH2-CH=C(CH3)-CH2-CH2-CH=C(CH3)2) to a chemical entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: farnesylation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Addition of a geranylgeranyl group (CH2-CH=C(CH3)-CH2-CH2-CH=C(CH3)-CH2-CH2-CH=C(CH3)-CH2-CH2-CH=C(CH3)2) to a chemical entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: geranylgeranylation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Covalent linkage to the protein ubiquitin.
@graph.rdfs:label: ubiquitination

@graph.rdfs:comment: Time during which some action is awaited.
@graph.rdfs:label: delay

@graph.rdfs:comment: A quantitative measure of an amount or property of an entity expressed in terms of another dimension, such as unit length, area or volume.
@graph.rdfs:label: density of an entity pool

@graph.rdfs:comment: The mass of an entity expressed with reference to another dimension, such as unit length, area or volume.
@graph.rdfs:label: mass density of an entity

@graph.rdfs:comment: Mass of an entity per unit volume.
@graph.rdfs:label: volume density of an entity

@graph.rdfs:comment: The mass of an entity per unit of surface area.
@graph.rdfs:label: area density of an entity

@graph.rdfs:comment: Mass of an entity per unit length.
@graph.rdfs:label: linear density of an entity

@graph.rdfs:comment: Representation of an entity that manifests, unfolds or develops through time, such as a discrete event, or a mutual or reciprocal action or influence that happens between participating physical entities, and/or other occurring entities.
@graph.rdfs:label: occurring entity representation

@graph.rdfs:comment: A phenomenon that takes place and which may be observable, or may be determined to have occurred as the result of an action or process.
@graph.rdfs:label: obsolete event

@graph.rdfs:comment: Addition of an hydroxyl group (-OH) to a chemical entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: hydroxylation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modelling approach, pioneered by Rene Thomas and Stuart Kaufman, where the evolution of a system is described by the transitions between discrete activity states of "genes" that control each other.
@graph.rdfs:label: logical framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: Entity that affects or is affected by an event.
@graph.rdfs:label: participant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: new synonym
@graph.rdfs:label: physical entity representation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Combining the influence of several entities or events in a unique influence.
@graph.rdfs:label: logical combination

@graph.rdfs:comment: The preceding event or participating entity cannot participate to the control.
@graph.rdfs:label: not

@graph.rdfs:comment: Regulation of the influence of a reaction participant by binding an effector to a binding site of the participant different of the site of the participant conveying the influence.
@graph.rdfs:label: allosteric control

@graph.rdfs:comment: A real thing that is defined by its physico-chemical structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: material entity

@graph.rdfs:comment: A real thing, defined by its properties or the actions it performs, rather than it physico-chemical structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: functional entity

@graph.rdfs:comment: A component that allows another component to pass through itself, possibly connecting different compartments.
@graph.rdfs:label: channel

@graph.rdfs:comment:
A locatable region of genomic sequence, corresponding to a unit of inheritance, which is associated with regulatory regions, transcribed regions and/or other functional sequence regions.

Sequence Ontology SO:0000704
@graph.rdfs:label: gene

@graph.rdfs:comment:
Participating entity that binds to a specific physical entity and initiates the response to that physical entity.The original concept of the receptor was introduced independently at the end of the 19th century by John Newport Langley (1852-1925) and Paul Ehrlich (1854-1915).

Langley JN.On the reaction of cells and of nerve-endings to certain poisons, chiefly as regards the reaction of striated muscle to nicotine and to curari. J Physiol. 1905 Dec 30;33(4-5):374-413.
@graph.rdfs:label: receptor

@graph.rdfs:comment:
Molecular entity mainly built-up by the repetition of pseudo-identical units.

CHEBI:33839
@graph.rdfs:label: macromolecule

@graph.rdfs:comment: Macromolecule whose sequence is encoded in the genome of living organisms.
@graph.rdfs:label: information macromolecule

@graph.rdfs:comment: Simple, non-repetitive chemical entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: simple chemical

@graph.rdfs:comment: Macromolecule whose sequence is not directly encoded in the genome.
@graph.rdfs:label: chemical macromolecule

@graph.rdfs:comment:
Macromolecule consisting of a large number of monosaccharide residues linked by glycosidic bonds.

CHEBI:18154
@graph.rdfs:label: polysaccharide

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: RNA
@graph.rdfs:label: ribonucleic acid

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: DNA
@graph.rdfs:label: deoxyribonucleic acid

@graph.rdfs:comment:
Naturally occurring macromolecule formed by the repetition of amino-acid residues linked by peptidic bonds. A polypeptide chain is synthesized by the ribosome.

CHEBI:16541
@graph.rdfs:label: polypeptide chain

@graph.rdfs:comment: Entity composed of several independant components that are not linked by covalent bonds.
@graph.rdfs:label: non-covalent complex

@graph.rdfs:comment: Measure of the degree to which an object opposes the passage of an electric current. The SI unit of electrical resistance is the ohm.
@graph.rdfs:label: electrical resistance

@graph.rdfs:comment: Parameter characterising a physical system or the environment, and independent of life's influence.
@graph.rdfs:label: physical characteristic

@graph.rdfs:comment: Parameter that depends on the biochemical properties of a system.
@graph.rdfs:label: biochemical parameter

@graph.rdfs:comment: Measure of how easily electricity flows along a certain path through an electrical element. The SI derived unit of conductance is the Siemens.
@graph.rdfs:label: conductance

@graph.rdfs:comment: Measure of the amount of electric charge stored (or separated) for a given electric potential. The unit of capacitance id the Farad.
@graph.rdfs:label: capacitance

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: electrical potential difference
@graph.rdfs:label: voltage

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: simple intersecting linear competitive inhibition of unireactant enzymes
@graph.rdfs:label: enzymatic rate law for simple competitive inhibition of irreversible unireactant enzymes by one inhibitor

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: Ki
@graph.rdfs:label: inhibitory constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: simple linear uncompetitive inhibition
@graph.rdfs:label: enzymatic rate law for simple uncompetitive inhibition of irreversible unireactant enzymes

@graph.rdfs:comment: Ratio of an equilibrium constant in a given condition by the same equilibrium constant is not fullfilled.
@graph.rdfs:label: relative equilibrium constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Ratio of the dissociation constant of an inhibitor from the complex enzyme-substrate on the dissociation constant of an inhibitor from the free enzyme.
@graph.rdfs:label: relative inhibition constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: simple intersecting linear mixed-type competitive inhibition
@graph.rdfs:label: enzymatic rate law for simple mixed-type inhibition of irreversible unireactant enzymes

@graph.rdfs:comment: Inhibition of a unireactant enzyme by one inhibitor that can bind to the complex enzyme-substrate and the free enzyme with the same equilibrium constant, and totally prevent the catalysis.
@graph.rdfs:label: enzymatic rate law for simple irreversible non-competitive inhibition of unireactant enzymes

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: mRNA
@graph.rdfs:label: messenger RNA

@graph.rdfs:comment: Pressure (symbol: p) is the force per unit area applied on a surface in a direction perpendicular to that surface. The unit of pressure is the Pascal (Pa), that is equal to 1 Newton per square meter.
@graph.rdfs:label: pressure

@graph.rdfs:comment: In biochemistry, a ligand is an effector, a physical entity that binds to a site on a receptor's surface by intermolecular forces.
@graph.rdfs:label: ligand

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: Keq
@graph.rdfs:label: equilibrium constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: Kd
@graph.rdfs:label: dissociation constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: Ka
@graph.rdfs:label: acid dissociation constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Participating entity that facilitates the movement of another physical entity from a defined subset of the physical environment (for instance a cellular compartment) to another.
@graph.rdfs:label: transporter

@graph.rdfs:comment: Material entity whose nature is unknown or irrelevant.
@graph.rdfs:label: material entity of unspecified nature

@graph.rdfs:comment: Non-covalent association of identical, or pseudo-identical, entities. By pseudo-identical entities, we mean biochemical elements that differ chemically, although remaining globally identical in structure and/or function. Examples are homologous subunits in an hetero-oligomeric receptor.
@graph.rdfs:label: multimer

@graph.rdfs:comment: Concentration of an active compound at which 50% of its maximal effect is observed. The EC50 is not a pure characteristic of the compound but depends on the conditions or the measurement.
@graph.rdfs:label: EC50

@graph.rdfs:comment: Also called half maximal inhibitory concentration, it represents the concentration of an inhibitor substance that is required to suppress 50% of an effect.
@graph.rdfs:label: IC50

@graph.rdfs:comment: Logical or physical subset of the event space that contains pools, that is sets of participants considered identical when it comes to the event they are involved into. A compartment can have any number of dimensions, including 0, and be of any size including null.
@graph.rdfs:label: functional compartment

@graph.rdfs:comment: Specific location of space, that can be bounded or not. A physical compartment can have 1, 2 or 3  dimensions.
@graph.rdfs:label: physical compartment

@graph.rdfs:comment: Entity defined by the absence of any actual object. An empty set is often used to represent the source of a creation process or the result of a degradation process.
@graph.rdfs:label: empty set

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modelling approach where the quantities of participants are considered continuous, and represented by real values. The associated simulation methods make use of differential equations. The models take into account the distribution of the entities and describe the spatial fluxes.
@graph.rdfs:label: spatial continuous framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modelling approach where the quantities of participants are considered continuous, and represented by real values. The associated simulation methods make use of differential equations. The models do not take into account the distribution of the entities and describe only the temporal fluxes.
@graph.rdfs:label: non-spatial continuous framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modelling approach where the quantities of participants are considered discrete, and represented by integer values. The associated simulation methods can be deterministic or stochastic. The models take into account the distribution of the entities and describe the spatial fluxes.
@graph.rdfs:label: spatial discrete framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modelling approach where the quantities of participants are considered discrete, and represented by integer values. The associated simulation methods can be deterministic or stochastic.The models do not take into account the distribution of the entities and describe only the temporal fluxes.
@graph.rdfs:label: non-spatial discrete framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: Non-covalent complex of one or more macromolecules and zero or more simple chemicals.
@graph.rdfs:label: macromolecular complex

@graph.rdfs:comment:
Macromolecular complex containing one or more polypeptide chains possibly associated with simple chemicals.

CHEBI:36080
@graph.rdfs:label: protein complex

@graph.rdfs:comment: Chemical entity that is engineered by a human-designed process ex-vivo rather than a produced by a living entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: synthetic chemical compound

@graph.rdfs:comment: Substance produced by metabolism or by a metabolic process.
@graph.rdfs:label: metabolite

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: Et
@graph.rdfs:label: total concentration of enzyme

@graph.rdfs:comment:
Constant representing the actual efficiency of an enzyme at a given concentration, taking into account its microscopic catalytic activity and the rates of substrate binding and dissociation.

NB. The symbol Vmax and the names maximum rate and maximum velocity are in widespread use although under normal circumstances there is no finite substrate concentration at which v = V and hence no maximum in the mathematical sense (Eur. J. Biochem. 128:281-291).
@graph.rdfs:label: total catalytic efficiency

@graph.rdfs:comment: Constant representing the actual efficiency of an enzyme, taking into account its microscopic catalytic activity and the rates of substrate binding and dissociation.
@graph.rdfs:label: catalytic efficiency

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: chemical potential
@graph.rdfs:label: biochemical potential

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: potential of hydrogen
@graph.rdfs:label: pH

@graph.rdfs:comment: Negative logarithm (base 10) of the activity of hydroxyde in a solution. In a diluted solution, this activity is equal to the concentration of ions HO-.
@graph.rdfs:label: pOH

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: dissociation potential
@graph.rdfs:label: pK

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: potential of acid
@graph.rdfs:label: pKa

@graph.rdfs:comment: Quantitative parameter that characterises a biochemical equilibrium.
@graph.rdfs:label: equilibrium or steady-state characteristic

@graph.rdfs:comment: Quantitative parameter that characterises a dissociation.
@graph.rdfs:label: dissociation characteristic

@graph.rdfs:comment: Quantitative parameter that characterises an acid-base reaction.
@graph.rdfs:label: acid dissociation characteristic

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: Precursor mRNA
@graph.rdfs:label: heterogeneous nuclear RNA

@graph.rdfs:comment: Completely processed single strand of messenger ribonucleic acid (mRNA), synthesized from a DNA template in the nucleus of a cell by transcription and containing copies of only the exons of a gene.
@graph.rdfs:label: mature messenger RNA

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: tRNA
@graph.rdfs:label: transfer RNA

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: rRNA
@graph.rdfs:label: ribosomal RNA

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: ribonucleic acid enzyme
@graph.rdfs:label: ribozyme

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: miRNA
@graph.rdfs:label: microRNA

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: siRNA
@graph.rdfs:label: small interfering RNA

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: snRNA
@graph.rdfs:label: small nuclear RNA

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: snoRNA
@graph.rdfs:label: small nucleolar RNA

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: kcatp
@graph.rdfs:label: product catalytic rate constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: reverse catalytic rate constant
@graph.rdfs:label: substrate catalytic rate constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: Kms
@graph.rdfs:label: Michaelis constant for substrate

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: Kmp
@graph.rdfs:label: Michaelis constant for product

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: Vmaxf
@graph.rdfs:label: forward maximal velocity

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: Vmaxr
@graph.rdfs:label: reverse maximal velocity

@graph.rdfs:comment: Kinetics of enzymes that react only with one substance, their substrate, and are not modulated by other compounds.
@graph.rdfs:label: enzymatic rate law for non-modulated unireactant enzymes

@graph.rdfs:comment: Chemical entity having a net electric charge.
@graph.rdfs:label: non-macromolecular ion

@graph.rdfs:comment: chemical entity possessing an unpaired electron.
@graph.rdfs:label: non-macromolecular radical

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: TSS
@graph.rdfs:label: transcription start site

@graph.rdfs:comment: Removal of a phosphate group (-H2PO4) from a chemical entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: dephosphorylation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Time interval over which a quantified entity is reduced to half its original value.
@graph.rdfs:label: half-life

@graph.rdfs:comment: Time taken by a quantity decreasing according to a mono-exponential decay to be divided by two. Sometimes called t1/2.
@graph.rdfs:label: half-life of an exponential decay

@graph.rdfs:comment: Monotonic decrease of a quantity proportionally to its value.
@graph.rdfs:label: monoexponential decay rate law

@graph.rdfs:comment:
RNA molecule that is not translated into a protein. 

Sequence Ontology SO:0000655
@graph.rdfs:label: non-coding RNA

@graph.rdfs:comment: Portion of DNA or RNA that is transcribed into another RNA, such as a messenger RNA or a non-coding RNA (for instance a transfert RNA or a ribosomal RNA).
@graph.rdfs:label: gene coding region

@graph.rdfs:comment: Entity participating in a physical or functional interaction.
@graph.rdfs:label: interactor

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: Ka
@graph.rdfs:label: association constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: kd
@graph.rdfs:label: dissociation rate constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Rate with which two components associate into a complex.
@graph.rdfs:label: bimolecular association rate constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Rate with which three components associate into a complex.
@graph.rdfs:label: trimolecular association rate constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Rate with which components associate into a complex.
@graph.rdfs:label: association rate constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Mutual or reciprocal action or influence between molecular entities.
@graph.rdfs:label: molecular or genetic interaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: A phenomenon whereby an observed phenotype, qualitative or quantative, is not explainable by the simple additive effects of the individual gene pertubations alone. Genetic interaction between perturbed genes is usually expected to generate a 'defective' phenotype. The level of defectiveness is often used to sub-classify this phenomenon.
@graph.rdfs:label: genetic interaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: Relationship between molecular entities, based on contacts, direct or indirect.
@graph.rdfs:label: molecular interaction

@graph.rdfs:comment:
Fundmental quantity of the measuring system used to sequence events, to compare the durations of events and the intervals between them, and to quantify the motions or the transformation of entities. The SI base unit for time is the SI second. The second is the duration of
9,192,631,770 periods of the radiation corresponding to the transition
between the two hyperfine levels of the ground state of the caesium 133
atom.
@graph.rdfs:label: time

@graph.rdfs:comment: Fundamental quantity of the measuring system used to sequence events, to compare the durations of events and the intervals between them, and to quantify the motions or the transformation of entities. The SI base unit for time is the SI second. The second is the duration of 9,192,631,770 periods of the radiation corresponding to the transition between the two hyperfine levels of the ground state of the caesium 133 atom.
@graph.rdfs:label: temporal measure

@graph.rdfs:comment: Amount of time during which an event persists.
@graph.rdfs:label: duration

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: mean lifetime
@graph.rdfs:label: exponential time constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: kinact
@graph.rdfs:label: inactivation rate constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: The speed of an enzymatic reaction at a defined concentration of substrate(s) and enzyme.
@graph.rdfs:label: forward reaction velocity

@graph.rdfs:comment: Numerical parameter that quantifies the reverse velocity of a chemical reaction independant of the reactant quantities. This parameter encompasses all the contributions to the velocity. It is to be used in a reaction modelled using a continuous framework.
@graph.rdfs:label: reverse zeroth order rate constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: The speed of an enzymatic reaction at a defined concentration of substrate(s) and enzyme.
@graph.rdfs:label: reverse reaction velocity

@graph.rdfs:comment: Fragment of a macromolecule that carries genetic information.
@graph.rdfs:label: informational molecule segment

@graph.rdfs:comment: Mathematical expression stating that a quantity is conserved in a system, whatever happens within the boundaries of that system.
@graph.rdfs:label: conservation law

@graph.rdfs:comment: Kinetic constant characterising a mono-exponential decay. It is the inverse of the mean lifetime of the continuant being decayed. Its unit is "per time".
@graph.rdfs:label: decay constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Biochemical networks can be affected by external influences. Those influences can be well-defined physical perturbations, such as a light pulse, or a change in temperature but also more complex of not well defined phenomena, for instance a biological process, an experimental setup, or a mutation.
@graph.rdfs:label: biological effect of a perturbation

@graph.rdfs:comment: A biochemical network can generate phenotypes or affects biological processes. Such processes can take place at different levels and are independent of the biochemical network itself.
@graph.rdfs:label: phenotype

@graph.rdfs:comment: A chemical moiety that exists under different forms but is not created nor destroyed in a biochemical system. In any given system such a conserved moiety is characterized by a finite number of particles that exist in the system and is invariant.
@graph.rdfs:label: mass conservation law

@graph.rdfs:comment: Region of a gene that is involved in the modulation of the expression of the gene.
@graph.rdfs:label: gene regulatory region

@graph.rdfs:comment: Michaelis constant derived or experimentally measured under non-equilibrium conditions.
@graph.rdfs:label: Michaelis constant in non-equilibrium situation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Michaelis constant derived using a steady-state assumption for enzyme-substrate and enzyme-product intermediates. For example see Briggs-Haldane equation (SBO:0000031).
@graph.rdfs:label: Michaelis constant in quasi-steady state situation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Michaelis constant derived assuming enzyme-substrate and enzyme-product intermediates are formed in consecutive irreversible reactions. The constant K is the ratio of the forward rate constants. For example see Van Slyke-Cullen equation (SBO:0000030).
@graph.rdfs:label: Michaelis constant in irreversible situation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Michaelis constant as determined in a reaction where the formation of the enzyme-substrate complex occurs at a much faster rate than subsequent steps, and so are assumed to be in a quasi-equilibrium situation. K is equivalent to an equilibrium constant. For example see Henri-Michaelis-Menten equation (SBO:0000029).
@graph.rdfs:label: Michaelis constant in fast equilibrium situation

@graph.rdfs:comment: connectedness between entities and/or interactions representing their relatedness or influence.
@graph.rdfs:label: relationship

@graph.rdfs:comment: A sequential series of actions, motions, or occurrences, such as chemical reactions, that affect one or more entities in a phenomenologically characteristic manner.
@graph.rdfs:label: process

@graph.rdfs:comment: Decomposition of a compound by reaction with water, where the hydroxyl and H groups are incorporated into different products
@graph.rdfs:label: hydrolysis

@graph.rdfs:comment: A reaction in which the principal reactant and principal product are isomers of each other
@graph.rdfs:label: isomerisation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Inhibition of a unireactant enzyme by competing substrates (Sa) that bind to the free enzyme on the same binding site. The enzyme does not catalyse the reactions in both directions.
@graph.rdfs:label: enzymatic rate law for inhibition of irreversible unireactant enzymes by competing substrates

@graph.rdfs:comment: Inhibition of a unireactant enzyme by two inhibitors that can bind once to the free enzyme and preclude the binding of the substrate. Binding of one inhibitor may affect binding of the other, or not. The enzymes do not catalyse the reactions in both directions.
@graph.rdfs:label: enzymatic rate law for simple competitive inhibition of irreversible unireactant enzymes by two non-exclusive inhibitors

@graph.rdfs:comment: number used as a multiplicative or exponential factor for quantities, expressions or functions
@graph.rdfs:label: biochemical coefficient

@graph.rdfs:comment: A multiplicative factor for quantities, expressions or functions
@graph.rdfs:label: biochemical proportionality coefficient

@graph.rdfs:comment: number used as an exponential factor for quantities, expressions or functions
@graph.rdfs:label: biochemical exponential coefficient

@graph.rdfs:comment: The coefficient used to quantify the effect on inhibition constants of multiple inhibitors binding non-exclusively to the enzyme.
@graph.rdfs:label: biochemical cooperative inhibition coefficient

@graph.rdfs:comment: Coefficient that quantifies the effect on inhibition constants of either binding of multiple substrates or inhibitors.
@graph.rdfs:label: biochemical inhibitory proportionality coefficient

@graph.rdfs:comment: The coefficient that describes the proportional change of Ks or Ki when inhibitor or substrate is bound, respectively, to the enzyme.
@graph.rdfs:label: biochemical cooperative inhibitor substrate coefficient

@graph.rdfs:comment: Inhibition of a unireactant enzyme by a competing substrate (Sa) that binds to the free enzyme on the same binding site. The enzyme does not catalyse the reactions in both directions.
@graph.rdfs:label: enzymatic rate law for inhibition of irreversible unireactant enzymes by single competing substrate

@graph.rdfs:comment: Inhibition of a unireactant enzyme by a competing product (P) that binds to the free enzyme on the same binding site. The enzyme does not catalyse the reactions in both directions.
@graph.rdfs:label: enzymatic rate law for competitive inhibition of irreversible unireactant enzyme by product

@graph.rdfs:comment: Inhibition of a unireactant enzyme by a competing substrate (Sa) that binds to the free enzyme on the same binding site, and competitive inhibition by a product (P) and an alternative product (Pa). The enzyme does not catalyse the reactions in both directions.
@graph.rdfs:label: enzymatic rate law for inhibition of irreversible unireactant enzymes by single competing substrate with product inhibition

@graph.rdfs:comment: A parameter value taken by a switch, which has a discrete set of values which can be alternated or switched between.
@graph.rdfs:label: switch value

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: binary switch
@graph.rdfs:label: boolean switch

@graph.rdfs:comment: A mathematical expression that describes a steady state situation
@graph.rdfs:label: steady state expression

@graph.rdfs:comment: Term to signify those material or conceptual entities that are identical in some respect within a frame of reference
@graph.rdfs:label: equivalence

@graph.rdfs:comment: Generation of a material or conceptual entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: production

@graph.rdfs:comment: Decrease in amount of a material or conceptual entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: consumption

@graph.rdfs:comment: An aggregation of interactions and entities into a single process.
@graph.rdfs:label: encapsulating process

@graph.rdfs:comment: An equivocal or conjectural process, whose existence is assumed but not proven.
@graph.rdfs:label: uncertain process

@graph.rdfs:comment: One or more processes that are not represented in certain representations or interpretations of a model.
@graph.rdfs:label: omitted process

@graph.rdfs:comment: Relationship between entities (material or conceptual) and logical operators, or between logical operators themselves.
@graph.rdfs:label: logical relationship

@graph.rdfs:comment: A process in which a carboxyl group (COOH) is removed from a molecule as carbon dioxide.
@graph.rdfs:label: decarboxylation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Removal of a carbonyl group (-C-O-) from a molecule, usually as carbon monoxide
@graph.rdfs:label: decarbonylation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Removal of an amine group from a molecule, often under the addition of water
@graph.rdfs:label: deamination

@graph.rdfs:comment: Covalent reaction that results in the transfer of a chemical group from one molecule to another.
@graph.rdfs:label: transfer of a chemical group

@graph.rdfs:comment: The transfer of an amino group between two molecules. Commonly in biology this is restricted to reactions between an amino acid and an alpha-keto carbonic acid, whereby the reacting amino acid is converted into an alpha-keto acid, and the alpha-keto acid reactant into an amino acid.
@graph.rdfs:label: transamination

@graph.rdfs:comment: Functional entity associated with or derived from a unit of inheritance.
@graph.rdfs:label: unit of genetic information

@graph.rdfs:comment: A material entity that is responsible for a perturbing effect
@graph.rdfs:label: perturbing agent

@graph.rdfs:comment: An entity that can be measured quantitatively
@graph.rdfs:label: observable

@graph.rdfs:comment: Control that precludes the execution of a process.
@graph.rdfs:label: absolute inhibition

@graph.rdfs:comment: Effect of a biological entity on biological structures or processes.
@graph.rdfs:label: biological activity

@graph.rdfs:comment: Entity that results from the interaction between other entities.
@graph.rdfs:label: interaction outcome

@graph.rdfs:comment: A compartment whose existence is inferred due to the presence of known material entities which must be bounded, allowing the creation of material entity pools.
@graph.rdfs:label: implicit compartment

@graph.rdfs:comment: Control that always triggers the controlled process.
@graph.rdfs:label: absolute stimulation

@graph.rdfs:comment: The potential action that a biological entity has on other entities. Example are enzymatic activity, binding activity etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: biological activity

@graph.rdfs:comment: The connectedness between entities as related by their position
@graph.rdfs:label: positional relationship

@graph.rdfs:comment: Positional relationship between entities on the same strand (e.g. in DNA), or on the same side.
@graph.rdfs:label: cis

@graph.rdfs:comment: Positional relationship between entities on different sides, or strands
@graph.rdfs:label: trans

@graph.rdfs:comment: One of the two values possible from a boolean switch, which equates to '1', 'on' or 'input'.
@graph.rdfs:label: true

@graph.rdfs:comment: One of the two values possible from a boolean switch, which equates to '0', 'off' or 'no input'.
@graph.rdfs:label: false

@graph.rdfs:comment: Non-covalent association between several independant complexes
@graph.rdfs:label: multimer of complexes

@graph.rdfs:comment: Non-covalent association between portions of macromolecules that carry genetic information
@graph.rdfs:label: multimer of informational molecule segment

@graph.rdfs:comment: Non-covalent association between several macromolecules
@graph.rdfs:label: multimer of macromolecules

@graph.rdfs:comment: Non-covalent association between several simple chemicals
@graph.rdfs:label: multimer of simple chemicals

@graph.rdfs:comment: Inhibitory constant for the binding of a given ligand with an isomeric form of an enzyme.
@graph.rdfs:label: isoinhibition constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: In reversible reactions this is the concentration of product that is required to achieve half activation or inhibition in Hill-type kinetics, in the absence of the substrate.
@graph.rdfs:label: pseudo-dissociation constant for product

@graph.rdfs:comment: In reversible reactions this is the concentration of substrate that is required to achieve half activation or inhibition in Hill-type kinetics, in the absence of the product.
@graph.rdfs:label: pseudo-dissociation constant for substrate

@graph.rdfs:comment: Reversible Hill-type kinetics represents the situation where a single substrate and product bind cooperatively and reversibly to the enzyme. Co-operativity is seen if the Hill coefficient (h) is greater than 1, indicating that the binding of one substrate (or product) molecule facilitates the binding of the next. The opposite effect is evident with a coefficient less than 1.
@graph.rdfs:label: reversible Hill-type enzymatic rate law

@graph.rdfs:comment: Reversible Hill-type kinetics in the presence of at least one modifier whose binding is affected by the presence of the substrate or product.
@graph.rdfs:label: modulated reversible Hill-type rate law

@graph.rdfs:comment: The modifier can be either an activator or inhibitor depending on the value of alpha (activator for values larger than 1, inhibitor for values smaller than 1; no effect if exactly 1). This reflects the effect of the presence of substrate and product on the binding of the modifier. The equation, derived by Hofmeyr and Cornish-Bowden (Comput. Appl. Biosci. 13, 377 - 385 (1997)
@graph.rdfs:label: modulated reversible Hill-type rate law with one modifier

The modifiers can be either activators or inhibitors depending on the values of and alpha (activators for values larger than 1, inhibitors for values smaller than 1; no effect if exactly 1). The assumption is that the binding of one modifier affects the binding of the second. Modifiers are assumed to bind at different sites.  The synergetic effects of the two modifiers depend on the parameter alpha (if unity then they are independent; if zero they compete for the same binding site). and reflect the effect of the presence of substrate and product on the binding of modifier A or modifier B. alphaA and  alphaB  factors account for the effect of substrate and product binding on the binding of modifier A and modifier B respectively. alphaAB accounts for the interaction of the modifiers on each others binding.
  (if < 1 Ma is inhibitor, if > 1 activator)
alpha_2 	: factor accounting for the effect of S and P on the binding of Mb

@graph.rdfs:label: catalytic site

@graph.rdfs:comment: A transmembrane domain is any three-dimensional protein structure which is thermodynamically stable in a membrane. This may be a single alpha helix, a stable complex of several transmembrane alpha helices, a transmembrane beta barrel, a beta-helix of gramicidin A, or any other structure.

@graph.rdfs:comment: A phenomenon whereby an observed phenotype, qualitative or quantative,  is not explainable by the simple additive effects of the individual gene pertubations alone. Genetic interaction between perturbed genes is usually expected to generate a 'defective' phenotype. The level of defectiveness is often used to sub-classify this phenomenon.
@graph.rdfs:label: genetic interaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: Genetic suppression is said to have occurred when the phenotypic effect of an initial mutation in a gene is less severe, or entirely negated, by a subsequent mutation.
@graph.rdfs:label: genetic suppression

@graph.rdfs:comment: Genetic enhancement is said to have occurred when the phenotypic effect of an initial mutation in a gene is made increasingly severe by a subsequent mutation.
@graph.rdfs:label: genetic enhancement

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synthetic lethality is said to have occurred where gene mutations, each of which map to a separate locus, fail to complement in an offspring to correct a phenotype, as would be expected.
@graph.rdfs:label: synthetic lethality

@graph.rdfs:comment: The numerical quantification of an entity pool. This may be expressed as, for example, the number of molecules or the number of moles of identical entities of which an specific entity pool is comprised.

@graph.rdfs:comment: The mass that comprises an entity pool.

@graph.rdfs:label: mass of enzyme

@graph.rdfs:comment: Amount, expressed as a number, of a specific enzyme comprising an entity pool. This may be expressed, for example, as the number of molecules, or the number of moles. The participant role 'enzymatic catalyst' is defined in SBO:0000460.

@graph.rdfs:label: concentration of modifier

@graph.rdfs:comment: The process by which two or more proteins interact non-covalently to form a protein complex (SBO:0000297).
@graph.rdfs:label: protein complex formation
modular rate law

@graph.rdfs:comment: The common modular rate law is a generalised form of reversible Michaelis Menten kinetics, using a denominator where each binding state of the enzyme is represented. It is assumed that substrates and products bind independently and randomly, and that substrates and products cannot be bound at the same time.
@graph.rdfs:label: common modular rate law

@graph.rdfs:comment: The direct binding modular rate law makes the assumption that both substrates and products bind simultaneously and in a single step, hence the total binding states possible enumerate to 3; nothing bound, substrates bound, and products bound. Substrates and products cannot be bound at the same time.
@graph.rdfs:label: direct binding modular rate law

@graph.rdfs:comment: The simultaneous binding modular rate law makes the assumption that substrates and products can be bound simultaneously, and in any combination.
@graph.rdfs:label: simultaneous binding modular rate law

@graph.rdfs:comment: For the power-law rate law, the denominator is set to be a constant, and the rate law does not saturate.
@graph.rdfs:label: power-law modular rate law

@graph.rdfs:comment:
Modular rate law where the D term is given by the square root of the product of
terms (c/KM)^m where c, KM, and m denote the concentrations, Michaelis constants, and molecularities, respectively, and the product is taken over all reactants and products involved in the reaction.
@graph.rdfs:label: force-dependent modular rate law

@graph.rdfs:comment:
An essential activator that affects the apparent value of the specificity
constant. Mechanistically, the activator would need to be bound before
reactant and product binding can take place.
@graph.rdfs:label: specific activator

@graph.rdfs:comment:
An essential activator that affects the apparent value of the catalytic
constant.
@graph.rdfs:label: catalytic activator

@graph.rdfs:comment:
An essential activator that affects the apparent value of the Michaelis
constant(s).
@graph.rdfs:label: binding activator

@graph.rdfs:comment:
Substance that, when bound, decreases enzymatic activity to a lower,
nonzero value, without itself being consumed or transformed by the
reaction, and without sterically hindering the interaction between
reactants. The enzyme-inhibitor complex does retain some basal level of activity.
@graph.rdfs:label: partial inhibitor

@graph.rdfs:comment:
Substance that, when bound, completely negates enzymatic activity, without
itself being consumed or transformed by the reaction, and without
sterically hindering the interaction between reactants. The inhibitor
binds to all enzyme species independently and with the same affinity,
completely inhibiting any enzymatic activity.
@graph.rdfs:label: complete inhibitor

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: membrane permeability
@graph.rdfs:label: ionic permeability

@graph.rdfs:comment: A quantitative parameter that represents a probability value, assigned to a specific event.
@graph.rdfs:label: probabilistic parameter

@graph.rdfs:comment: A ratio that represents the quantity of a defined constituent entity over the total number of all constituent entities present.
@graph.rdfs:label: fraction of an entity pool

@graph.rdfs:comment: The number of moles of a constituent entity, divided by the total number of all constituent entities present in a system.
@graph.rdfs:label: mole fraction

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: R0
@graph.rdfs:label: basic reproductive ratio

@graph.rdfs:comment: A nonspecific coalescence of misfolded proteins which may or may not form a precipitate, depending upon particle size.
@graph.rdfs:label: protein aggregate

@graph.rdfs:comment: Supplementary information relating to a primary item of data, traditionally termed 'data about data'. It can describe, for example, the location or type of the data, or its relationship to other data.
@graph.rdfs:label: metadata representation

@graph.rdfs:comment: A value, numerical or symbolic, that defines certain characteristics of systems or system functions, or is necessary in their derivation.
@graph.rdfs:label: systems description parameter

@graph.rdfs:comment: A non-numerical value that defines certain characteristics of systems or system functions.
@graph.rdfs:label: qualitative systems description parameter

@graph.rdfs:comment: Equationally defined algebraic framework usually interpreted as a two-valued logic using the basic Boolean operations (conjunction, disjunction and negation), together with the constants '0' and '1' denoting false and true values, respectively.
@graph.rdfs:label: boolean logical framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: Extension of the boolean logical framework which associates a defined number of possible integer values (states) with the variables.
@graph.rdfs:label: multi-valued logical framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: Extension of the Boolean logical framework which allows intermediate or undetermined values for the logical variables.
@graph.rdfs:label: fuzzy logical framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: Supplementary information that does not modify the semantics of the presented information.
@graph.rdfs:label: annotation

@graph.rdfs:comment: The use of an abbreviated name, taken from a controlled vocabulary of terms, which is used to represent some information about the entity to which it is attached.
@graph.rdfs:label: controlled short label

@graph.rdfs:comment: Additional information that supplements existing data, usually in a document, by providing a link to more detailed information, which is held externally, or elsewhere.
@graph.rdfs:label: reference annotation

@graph.rdfs:comment: An annotation which directs one to information contained within a published body of knowledge, usually a book or scientific journal.
@graph.rdfs:label: bibliographical reference

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: db xref
@graph.rdfs:label: database cross reference

@graph.rdfs:comment: Annotation which complies with the full set of defined rules in its construction.
@graph.rdfs:label: controlled annotation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Annotation which does not comply with, or is not restricted by, any rules in its construction. Examples would include free text annotations.
@graph.rdfs:label: uncontrolled annotation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Annotation that directly incorporates information into the body of a document.
@graph.rdfs:label: embedded annotation

@graph.rdfs:comment: A measure of enzyme activity under standard conditions, at a specific substrate concentration (usually saturation), expressed as the amount of product formed per unit time, per amount of enzyme. This is often expressed as micromol per min per mg, rather than the less practical official unit, Katal (1 mol per second).
@graph.rdfs:label: specific activity

@graph.rdfs:comment: A measure of the amount of active enzyme present, expressed under specified conditions. This is often expressed as micromol per min (also known as enzyme unit, U), rather than the less practical official SI unit, Katal (1 mol per second). Enzyme activity normally refers to the natural substrate for the enzyme, but can also be given for standardised substrates such as gelatin, where it is then referred to as GDU (Gelatin Digesting Units).
@graph.rdfs:label: enzyme activity

@graph.rdfs:comment: Reaction scheme in which the reaction velocity is direct proportional to the activity or concentration of a single molecular species. The reaction scheme does not include any reverse process that creates the reactants from the products. The change of a product quantity is proportional to the quantity of the stimulator. It is to be used in a reaction modelled using a continuous framework.
@graph.rdfs:label: mass action rate law for first order irreversible reactions, single essential stimulator, continuous scheme

@graph.rdfs:comment: Reaction scheme in which the reaction velocity is direct proportional to the activity or quantity of a single molecular species. The reaction scheme does not include any reverse process that creates the reactants from the products. The change of a product quantity is proportional to the quantity of the stimulator. It is to be used in a reaction modelled using a discrete framework.
@graph.rdfs:label: mass action rate law for first order irreversible reactions, single essential stimulator, discrete scheme

@graph.rdfs:comment: Reaction scheme where the products are created from a reactant and the change of a product quantity is proportional to the product of the reactant and the stimulator activities. The reaction scheme does not include any reverse process that creates the reactant from the products. The change of a product quantity is proportional to the quantity of the reactant and the stimulator.
@graph.rdfs:label: mass action like rate law for second order irreversible reactions, one reactant, one essential stimulator

@graph.rdfs:comment: Reaction scheme where the products are created from a reactant and the change of a product quantity is proportional to the product of the reactant and the stimulator activities. The reaction scheme does not include any reverse process that creates the reactant from the products. The change of a product quantity is proportional to the quantity of the reactant and the stimulator. It is to be used in a reaction modelled using a continuous framework.
@graph.rdfs:label: mass action like rate law for second order irreversible reactions, one reactant, one essential stimulator, continuous scheme

@graph.rdfs:comment: Reaction scheme where the products are created from a reactant and the change of a product quantity is proportional to the product of the reactant and the stimulator quantities. The reaction scheme does not include any reverse process that creates the reactant from the products. The change of a product quantity is proportional to the quantity of the reactant and the stimulator. It is to be used in a reaction modelled using a discrete framework.
@graph.rdfs:label: mass action like rate law for second order irreversible reactions, one reactant, one essential stimulator, discrete scheme

@graph.rdfs:comment: A physical constant that is required in the calculation of a system parameter.
@graph.rdfs:label: systems description constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: The permeability of an ion through a channel or membrane expressed in relation to the reference ion, which is given the value 1. For example, if a membrane is most permeable to K+, then that is assigned the reference permeability value of 1, and the value for Na+ may be 0.05.
@graph.rdfs:label: relative permeability

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: molar gas constant
@graph.rdfs:label: universal gas constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Named after Michael Faraday, it is the magnitude of electric charge per mole of electrons. It has the value 96,485.3365 C/mol (Coulombs per Mole), and the symbol F.
@graph.rdfs:label: Faraday constant

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: Goldman-Hodgkin-Katz voltage equation
@graph.rdfs:label: Goldman equation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: reversal potential
@graph.rdfs:label: Nernst potential

@graph.rdfs:comment:
Parameters used in the study of thermodynamics, a physical science that
pertains to the relationship between heat and other forms of energy such
as 'work done' in material bodies.
@graph.rdfs:label: thermodynamic parameter

@graph.rdfs:comment:
A thermodynamic potential whose natural variables are entropy (S) and
pressure (p). The enthalpy of a system, measured in Joules (J), is defined
as H = U + pV (where H is enthalpy, U is the internal energy, p is the
pressure at the system boundary, and V is the system volume).
symbol: H
@graph.rdfs:label: enthalpy

@graph.rdfs:comment:
Change in enthalpy observed in the constituents of a thermodynamic system
when undergoing a transformation or chemical reaction. This is the
preferred way of expressing the energy changes to a system at constant
pressure, since enthalpy itself cannot be directly measured. The enthalpy
change is positive in endothermic reactions, negative in exothermic
reactions, and is defined as the difference between the final and initial enthalpy of the system under study: ΔH = Hf - Hi. The standard unit of measure is J. Symbol: ΔH
@graph.rdfs:label: enthalpy change

@graph.rdfs:comment:
The enthalpy change observed in a constituent of a thermodynamic system
when one mole of a compound, in its standard state, is formed from its
elementary antecedents, in their standard state(s), under standard
conditions (1 bar). The standard unit of measure is kJ/mol.
Symbol: DeltaHf0, DeltafH0
@graph.rdfs:label: standard enthalpy of formation

@graph.rdfs:comment:
The enthalpy change observed in a constituent of a thermodynamic system
when one mole of substance reacts completely, under standard conditions (1
bar). The standard unit of measure is kJ/mol.
Symbol: DeltaHr0, DeltarH0
@graph.rdfs:label: standard enthalpy of reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment:
A thermodynamic property which acts as a measure of the state of disorder
of a system. Its natural variables are the internal energy (U) and the
volume (V). It is defined by dS = (1/T)dU + (p/T)dV. The second law of
thermodynamics states that in an isolated system, natural processes tend
to increase in disorder or entropy. The standard unit of measure is Joules
per Kelvin (J/K).
symbol: S
@graph.rdfs:label: entropy

@graph.rdfs:comment:
