than zero, there is an implied increase in the disorder of a system, for
example during a reaction, and decreased disorder where the values are
less than zero. The entropy change of a process is defined as the initial
system entropy value minus the final entropy value: DeltaS = Sf - Si. The
standard unit of measure is J/K.
symbol: DeltaS
@graph.rdfs:label: entropy change

@graph.rdfs:comment:
The entropy change observed in a thermodynamic system when one mole of
substance reacts completely, under standard conditions (1 bar).  The
standard unit of measure is kJ/(mol K). This can be calculated using the
entropies for products and reactants: DeltaS(reaction)=sum DeltaS (products) - sum DeltaS reactants. The standard unit of measure is kJ/(mol K).
symbol: DeltaSro
@graph.rdfs:label: standard entropy of reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment:
The change in entropy associated with the formation of one mole of a
substance from its elements in their standard states under standard
conditions (1 bar). The standard unit of measure is kJ/(mol K).
symbol: DeltaSfo
@graph.rdfs:label: standard entropy of formation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: Gibbs function
@graph.rdfs:label: Gibbs free energy

@graph.rdfs:comment:
The increase or decrease of the Gibbs free energy of a system. During a
reaction, this is equal to the change in enthalpy of the system minus the
change in the product of the temperature times the entropy of the system: ΔG = ΔH - T ΔS. A negative value indicates that the reaction will be favoured and will
release energy. The magnitude of the value indicates how far the reaction
is from equilibrium, where there will be no free energy change. The
standard unit of measure is kJ/mol. Symbol: ΔG.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gibbs free energy change

@graph.rdfs:comment: The change in Gibbs free energy associated with the formation of 1 mole of substance from elements in their standard states under standard conditions (1 bar). For aqueous solutions, each solute must be present in 1M concentration. The standard unit of measure is kJ/mol. Symbol: ΔGf°.
@graph.rdfs:label: standard Gibbs free energy of formation

@graph.rdfs:comment:
The Gibbs free energy change observed in a thermodynamic system when one
mole of substance reacts completely, under standard conditions (1 bar). For aqueous solutions, each solute must be present in 1M concentration. The standard unit of measure is kJ/mol. Symbol: ΔG°.
@graph.rdfs:label: standard Gibbs free energy of reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: A duration of time after which a phase shift occurs.
@graph.rdfs:label: temporal offset

@graph.rdfs:comment: The total length of time over which a model is simulated, where the time scale is indicated within the model simulation.
@graph.rdfs:label: simulation duration

@graph.rdfs:comment: A conceptualisation of time which is intrinsic to a mathematical model, and which can be used to describe other variables or parameters of the model.
@graph.rdfs:label: model time

@graph.rdfs:comment: A transport reaction which results in the entry of the transported entity, into the cell.
@graph.rdfs:label: transcellular membrane influx reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: A transport reaction which results in the removal of the transported entity from the cell.
@graph.rdfs:label: transcellular membrane efflux reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: A composite biochemical process through which a gene sequence is fully converted into mature gene products. These gene products may include RNA species as well as proteins, and the process encompasses all intermediate steps required to generate the active form of the gene product.
@graph.rdfs:label: genetic production

@graph.rdfs:comment: A stretch of DNA upstream of a transcription start site, to which a promoter and other transcription factors may bind to initiate or regulate expression.
@graph.rdfs:label: promoter

@graph.rdfs:comment: A process that can modify the state of petri net 'places'[SBO:0000593].
@graph.rdfs:label: petri net transition

@graph.rdfs:comment: A discrete value attributed to an entity pool.
@graph.rdfs:label: discrete amount of an entity pool

@graph.rdfs:comment: A defined entity pool state which can be modified by a petri net transition [SBO:0000591].
@graph.rdfs:label: petri net place

@graph.rdfs:comment: A participant whose presence does not alter the velocity of a process or event.
@graph.rdfs:label: neutral participant

@graph.rdfs:comment:
A modifier that can exhibit either inhibitory or stimulatory effects on a
process depending on the context in which it occurs. For example, the observed effect may be dependent upon the concentration of the modifier.
@graph.rdfs:label: dual-activity modifier

@graph.rdfs:comment: A modifier whose activity is not known or has not been specified.
@graph.rdfs:label: modifier of unknown activity

@graph.rdfs:comment: A silencer is a modifier which acts in a manner that completely prevents an event or process from occurring. For example, a silencer in gene expression is usually a transcription factor that binds a DNA sequence in such a way as to completely prevent the binding of RNA polymerase, and thus fully suppresses transcription.
@graph.rdfs:label: silencer

@graph.rdfs:comment: A region of DNA to which various transcription factors and RNA polymerase must bind in order to initiate transcription for a gene.
@graph.rdfs:label: promoter

@graph.rdfs:comment: A denotement that specifies a point of contact between variables or submodels in a hierarchical model.
@graph.rdfs:label: port

@graph.rdfs:comment: A connection point to an element in a model that indicates that the element's mathematical interpretation is defined outside the model.
@graph.rdfs:label: input port

@graph.rdfs:comment: A connection point to an element in a model that indicates that the element's mathematical interpretation is defined within the model.
@graph.rdfs:label: output port

@graph.rdfs:comment: A parameter that takes only logical values.
@graph.rdfs:label: logical parameter

@graph.rdfs:comment: A substance that is produced in a chemical reaction but is not itself the primary product or focus of that reaction. Examples include, but are not limited to, currency compounds such as ATP, NADPH and protons.
@graph.rdfs:label: side product

@graph.rdfs:comment: A substance that is consumed in a chemical reaction but is not itself the primary substrate or focus of that reaction. Examples include, but are not limited to, currency compounds such as ATP, NADPH and protons.
@graph.rdfs:label: side substrate

@graph.rdfs:comment: A receptor where binding occurs through strong intermolecular forces such as Van der Waals, hydrogen bonds or ionic bonds.
@graph.rdfs:label: high affinity receptor

@graph.rdfs:comment: A receptor where binding occurs through weak intermolecular forces.
@graph.rdfs:label: low affinity receptor

@graph.rdfs:comment: A macromolecular complex composed of two monomeric units, which may or may not be identical. Monomers are usually non-covalently bound.
@graph.rdfs:label: dimer

@graph.rdfs:comment: A macromolecular complex composed of precisely two identical monomeric units, which are usually non-covalently bound.
@graph.rdfs:label: homodimer

@graph.rdfs:comment: A macromolecular complex composed of precisely two non-identical monomeric units, which are usually non-covalently bound.
@graph.rdfs:label: heterodimer

@graph.rdfs:comment: A measure of the rate of growth of an organism, usually in culture. This can be expressed as increase in cell number or, more usually as an increase in dry weight of cells (grams), measured over a unit time period. Usually expressed as hour -1.
@graph.rdfs:label: growth rate

@graph.rdfs:comment: Under nutrient limited conditions, it may be assumed that enzymes are operating below their maximal capacity (Kcat). Keff represents the lumped turnover rate of a reaction, expressed in units per time.
@graph.rdfs:label: effective catalytic rate

@graph.rdfs:comment: The velocity at which a reaction occurs. This may be calculated through the accumulation of a product or consumption of a reactant, and expressed using entity concentrations or amounts per time interval. The rate of reaction may be influenced by temperature, pressure and other factors. Rate of reaction is often referred to as reaction rate or metabolic flux.
@graph.rdfs:label: rate of reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: Parameters that pertain to chemical reactions.
@graph.rdfs:label: reaction parameter

@graph.rdfs:comment: Rate of reaction expressed as a change in concentration over time.
@graph.rdfs:label: rate of reaction (concentration)

@graph.rdfs:comment: Rate of reaction expressed as a change in enumerated quantity over time.
@graph.rdfs:label: rate of reaction (amount)

@graph.rdfs:comment: The extent of a reaction is a measure of how far a reaction has proceeded towards equilibrium. It is denoted by the Greek letter Î¾ and is expressed in moles.
@graph.rdfs:label: extent of reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: The Gibbs free energy change observed in a thermodynamic system when a substance undergoes a reaction under non standard conditions. The unit of measure is kJ/mol. Symbol: ΔG.
@graph.rdfs:label: Gibbs free energy of reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: thermodynamic driving force
@graph.rdfs:label: reaction affinity

@graph.rdfs:comment: A Gibbs free energy that is calculated from the standard Gibbs value (at 298K), and extrapolated to a desired pH and ionic strength, and may be determined at a different temperature. Symbol: ΔG´.
@graph.rdfs:label: transformed Gibbs free energy change

@graph.rdfs:comment: A Gibbs free energy of reaction that is calculated from the standard Gibbs value (at 298K), and extrapolated to a desired pH and ionic strength, and may be determined at a different temperature. Symbol ΔG´.
@graph.rdfs:label: transformed standard Gibbs free energy of reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: A Gibbs free energy of formation that is calculated from the standard Gibbs value (at 298K), and extrapolated to a desired pH and ionic strength, and may be determined at a different temperature. Symbol ΔGf´.
@graph.rdfs:label: transformed standard Gibbs free energy of formation

@graph.rdfs:comment: The Gibbs free energy change observed in a thermodynamic system when a substance undergoes a reaction under non standard conditions, which is extrapolated to a desired pH and ionic strength, and may be determined at a different temperature. Symbol: ΔG´.
@graph.rdfs:label: transformed Gibbs free energy of reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: A combined (weighted) measure of the concentration of all electrolytes present in a solution. It is calculated as a half of the sum over all the ions in the solution multiplied by the square of individual ionic valencies. Monovalent electrolytes have a concentration equal to their ionic strength while multivalent electrolytes have greater ionic strength, directly proportional to ionic valency. Symbol: I
@graph.rdfs:label: ionic strength

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modelling approach, typically used for metabolic models, where the flow of metabolites (flux) through a network can be calculated. This approach will generally produce a set of solutions (solution space), which may be reduced using objective functions and constraints on individual fluxes.
@graph.rdfs:label: flux balance framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: A parameter that limits the upper or lower value that a flux may assume. This parameter may be determined experimentally, or may be the result of theoretical investigation.
@graph.rdfs:label: flux bound

@graph.rdfs:comment: A value used for flux bound in cases where a precise value, supported experimentally or theoretically, is not available.
@graph.rdfs:label: default flux bound

@graph.rdfs:comment: A modeling process to provide matter influx or efflux to a model, for example to replenish a metabolic network with raw materials (eg carbon / energy sources). Such reactions are conceptual, created solely for modeling purposes, and do not have a physical correspondence. Exchange reactions, often represented as 'R_EX_', can operate in the negative (uptake) direction or positive (secretion) direction. By convention, a negative flux through an exchange reaction represents uptake of the corresponding metabolite, and a positive flux represent discharge.
@graph.rdfs:label: exchange reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: A modeling process analogous to exchange reaction, but which operates upon "internal" metabolites. Metabolites that are consumed by these reactions are assumed to be used in intra-cellular processes that are not part of the model. Demand reactions, often represented 'R_DM_', can also deliver metabolites (from intra-cellular processes that are not considered in the model).
@graph.rdfs:label: demand reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: Biomass production, often represented 'R_BIOMASS_', is usually the optimization target reaction of constraint-based models, and can consume multiple reactants to produce multiple products. It is also assumed that parts of the reactants are also consumed in unrepresented processes and hence products do not have to reflect all the atom composition of the reactants. Formulation of a biomass production process entails definition of the macromolecular content (eg. cellular protein fraction), metabolic constitution of each fraction (eg. amino acids), and subsequently the atomic composition (eg. nitrogen atoms). More complex biomass functions can additionally incorporate details of essential vitamins and cofactors required for growth.
@graph.rdfs:label: biomass production

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: maintenance energy
@graph.rdfs:label: ATP maintenance

@graph.rdfs:comment: A conceptual process used for modeling purposes, often created solely to complete model structure, with respect to providing inflow or outflow of matter or material. Unlike other reactions, pseudoreactions are not usually subjected to mass balance considerations.
@graph.rdfs:label: pseudoreaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: source/sink
@graph.rdfs:label: sink reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: Term used to indicate the grouping of model components, largely reactions, by some criterion, often processual. This can be used to indicate, for example, the subsystem of a model that is concerned with 'transport'. A designated subsystem includes reactions annotated with the term, as well as reactions participants such as enzymes, modifiers and genes encoding these subsystem components.
@graph.rdfs:label: subsystem

@graph.rdfs:comment: Fragment or region of a DNA macromolecule.
@graph.rdfs:label: DNA segment

@graph.rdfs:comment: Fragment or region of an RNA macromolecule.
@graph.rdfs:label: RNA segment

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: positive allosteric modulation
@graph.rdfs:label: allosteric activator

@graph.rdfs:comment: Describes an activator (ligand) which binds to the enzyme, which does not result in a conformational change, but which enhances the enzyme's activity.
@graph.rdfs:label: non-allosteric activator

@graph.rdfs:comment: An inhibitor which binds irreversibly with the enzyme such that it cannot be removed, and abolishes enzymatic function.
@graph.rdfs:label: irreversible inhibitor

@graph.rdfs:comment: An inhibitor whose binding to an enzyme results in a conformational change, resulting in a loss of enzymatic activity. This activity can be restored upon removal of the inhibitor.
@graph.rdfs:label: allosteric inhibitor

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: anti-competitive inhibitor
@graph.rdfs:label: uncompetitive inhibitor

@graph.rdfs:comment: An enumeration of the concentration of magnesium (Mg) in solution (pMg = -log10[Mg2+]).
@graph.rdfs:label: pMg

@graph.rdfs:comment: Conceptual or material entity that is the object of an inhibition process, and is acted upon by an inhibitor.
@graph.rdfs:label: inhibited

@graph.rdfs:comment: Conceptual or material entity that is the object of a stimulation process, and is acted upon by a stimulator.
@graph.rdfs:label: stimulated

@graph.rdfs:comment: Conceptual or material entity that is the object of a modification process, and is acted upon by a modifier.
@graph.rdfs:label: modified

@graph.rdfs:comment: An entity that acts as the starting material for genetic production (http://identifiers.org/biomodels.sbo/SBO:0000589).
@graph.rdfs:label: template

@graph.rdfs:comment: Reaction scheme where the products are created from the reactants and the change of a product quantity is proportional to the product of reactant activities. The reaction scheme includes a reverse process that creates the reactants from the products. It is to be used in a reaction modelled using a continuous framework.
@graph.rdfs:label: mass action rate law for reversible reactions, continuous schema

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: molecular weight
@graph.rdfs:label: molecular mass

@graph.rdfs:comment: Synonym: protein molecular weight
@graph.rdfs:label: protein molecular mass

@graph.rdfs:comment: A composite representation of material entities required for organismal growth. It includes macromolecular content (eg. cellular protein fraction), metabolic constitution of each fraction (eg. amino acids), and atomic composition (eg. nitrogen atoms).
@graph.rdfs:label: biomass

@graph.rdfs:comment: A sequential series of actions, motions, or occurrences, such as chemical reactions, where a reversal of states that bring the system back to its original state in a characteristic manner occurs.
@graph.rdfs:label: reversible process

@graph.rdfs:comment: A sequential series of actions, motions, or occurrences, such as chemical reactions, where a reversal of states that bring the system back to its original state in a characteristic manner does not occur.
@graph.rdfs:label: irreversible process

@graph.rdfs:comment: A chemical reaction in which one or more monomer molecules combine to form a larger polymer molecule with repeated structural units.
@graph.rdfs:label: polymerization

@graph.rdfs:comment: A chemical reaction in which a large polymer breaks into its constituent monomers (or mixture of monomers).
@graph.rdfs:label: depolymerization

@graph.rdfs:comment: A biochemical process involving the simultaneous transport of two or more substances across a membrane via a protein or protein complex.
@graph.rdfs:label: co-transport reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: The movement of an entity/entities across a biological membrane mediated by a transporter protein.
@graph.rdfs:label: transport reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: A conformational change in a protein resulting in its activation.
@graph.rdfs:label: activation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Protein assisted movement of molecules across a membrane from a region of low concentration to high concentration involving the consumption of cellular energy (ATP molecules).
@graph.rdfs:label: active transport

@graph.rdfs:comment: Movement of molecules without the need for external energy, and usually from a region of high concentration to low concentration.
@graph.rdfs:label: passive transport

@graph.rdfs:comment: A membrane protein mediated transport of two ore more molecules in the same relative direction across a membrane.
@graph.rdfs:label: symporter-mediated transport

@graph.rdfs:comment: A membrane protein mediated transport of two or more molecules in opposite directions across a membrane.
@graph.rdfs:label: antiporter-mediated transport

@graph.rdfs:comment: Total amount that can be contained or produced by a specific entity. This can refer to diverse items, such as the carrying capacity of a membrane with respect to proteins, the capacity of high-energy phosphate bonds, or the maximal count of bacteria in the gut, etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: capacity

@graph.rdfs:comment: Occopancy is a quantitative systemic property that indicates which number of available places is occupied. This can refer to diverse things, such as the number of occupied high-energy phosphate bonds in ATP, the number of bacteria in the gut, or the number of electrons loaded onto redox carriers, etc.
@graph.rdfs:label: occupancy

@graph.rdfs:comment: Fractional occupancy is a quantitative dynamic property of a system that can be calculated as the fraction of occupancy over capacity.
@graph.rdfs:label: fractional occupancy

@graph.rdfs:comment: an entity which physical constituents are partially or totally contained in a defined compartment.
@graph.rdfs:label: contained entity

@graph.rdfs:comment: a conformation changes to a protein leading to its inactivation
@graph.rdfs:label: inactivation

@graph.rdfs:comment: describes the number of amino acids,nucleic acid in a protein/DNA/RNA chain
@graph.rdfs:label: chain length

@graph.rdfs:comment: length of amino acid sequence in a protein
@graph.rdfs:label: protein chain length

@graph.rdfs:comment: output generated as biomass or product from a/set of chemical reaction/s.
@graph.rdfs:label: yield

@graph.rdfs:comment: generation of biomass for an substrate through a defined reaction/s.
@graph.rdfs:label: biomass yield on substrate

@graph.rdfs:comment: generation of product from substrate in a defined chemical reaction.
@graph.rdfs:label: product yield on substrate

@graph.rdfs:comment: agent driving non-enzymatic reaction. Non-enzymatic reactions resemble catalytic mechanisms as found in all major enzyme classes and occur spontaneously, small molecule (e.g. metal-) catalyzed or light-induced.
@graph.rdfs:label: non-enzymatic catalyst

@graph.rdfs:comment: Reaction with no catalyst (no enzyme in particular) is needed to proceed.
@graph.rdfs:label: spontaneous reaction

@graph.rdfs:comment: it represent the catalytic rate driving the reaction in forward direction.
@graph.rdfs:label: forward effective catalytic rate

@graph.rdfs:comment: it represent the catalytic rate driving the reaction in backward direction.
@graph.rdfs:label: reverse effective catalytic rate

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modeling approach where the quantities of participants are considered deterministic continuous variables, and represented by real values. The associated simulation methods make use of ordinary differential equations.
@graph.rdfs:label: deterministic non-spatial continuous framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modeling approach where the quantities of participants are considered stochastic continuous variables, and represented by real values. The associated simulation methods make use of stochastic differential equations. The models do take into account the distribution of the entities.
@graph.rdfs:label: stochastic non-spatial continuous framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modeling approach which tracks the sizes of populations of participants in each spatial localization. For biochemical simulations, such populations could represent types of molecular species.
@graph.rdfs:label: population-based discrete spatial simulation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modeling approach which tracks the state of individual particles in each spatial localization. For biochemical simulations, such particles could represent individual molecules.
@graph.rdfs:label: particle-based discrete spatial simulation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modeling approach which tracks the sizes of populations of participants with minimal or no spatial resolution. For biochemical simulations, such populations could represent types of molecular species.
@graph.rdfs:label: population-based discrete non-spatial simulation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modeling approach which tracks the state of individual particles with miimal or no spatial resolution. For biochemical simulations, such particles could represent individual molecules.
@graph.rdfs:label: particle-based discrete non-spatial simulation

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modeling approach which combines multiple canonical modeling frameworks. For example, a hybrid model could consider both continuous (represented by real values) and discrete (represented by integers) participants. Hybrid models are executed with hybrid simulation algorithms. For example, a hybrid continuous-discrete model may be simulation using a combination of stochastic simulation and ordinary differential equations.
@graph.rdfs:label: hybrid framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modeling approach which combines multiple canonical spatial modeling frameworks. For example, a hybrid model could consider both continuous (represented by real values) and discrete (represented by integers) participants. Hybrid models are executed with hybrid simulation algorithms. For example, a hybrid continuous-discrete model may be simulation using a combination of stochastic simulation and partial differential equations.
@graph.rdfs:label: hybrid spatial framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modeling approach which combines multiple canonical non-spatial modeling frameworks. For example, a hybrid model could consider both continuous (represented by real values) and discrete (represented by integers) participants. Hybrid models are executed with hybrid simulation algorithms. For example, a hybrid continuous-discrete model may be simulation using a combination of stochastic simulation and ordinary differential equations.
@graph.rdfs:label: hybrid non-spatial framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modeling approach which combines flux-balance [SBO:0000624] and deterministic continuous non-spatial [SBO:0000675] simulation. For example, a metabolic network could be simulated using flux balance analysis, while a signaling network could be co-simulated with a method for integrating ordinary differential equations.
@graph.rdfs:label: hybrid flux balance-deterministic continuous non-spatial framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modeling approach which combines flux-balance [SBO:0000624] and discrete non-spatial [SBO:0000295] simulation. For example, a metabolic network could be simulated using flux balance analysis, while the synthesis and turnover of enzymes could be co-simulated with a discrete simulation method such as Gillespie's algorithm.
@graph.rdfs:label: hybrid flux balance-discrete non-spatial framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modeling approach which combines flux-balance [SBO:0000624], non-spatial deterministic continuous [SBO:0000675], and logical [SBO:0000234] simulation. For example, a metabolic network could be simulated using flux balance analysis, while the expression metabolic enzymes could be co-simulated with a logical simulation method and a signaling network could be co-simulated with a method for integrating ordinary differential equations such as CVODE.
@graph.rdfs:label: hybrid flux balance-logical-deterministic continuous non-spatial framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modeling approach which combines flux-balance [SBO:0000624] and logical [SBO:0000234] simulation. For example, a metabolic network could be simulated using flux balance analysis, while the expression metabolic enzymes could be co-simulated with a logical simulation method.
@graph.rdfs:label: hybrid flux balance-logical non-spatial framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modeling approach which combines logical [SBO:0000234] and non-spatial discrete [SBO:0000295] simulation. For example, the MaBoSS simulation method simulates logical regulatory graphs with an algorithm that is similar to Gillespie's algorithm.
@graph.rdfs:label: hybrid flux logical-discrete non-spatial framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modeling approach which combines continuous [SBO:0000293] and discrete [SBO:0000295] simulation, where some participants are represented as continuous variables and others are represented as discrete variables, without a detailed spatial representation of each participant. For example, a model may be simulated using a combination of a discrete simulation method such as Gillespie's algorithm and an ordinary differential equations integration method such as CVODE.
@graph.rdfs:label: hybrid continuous-discrete non-spatial framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modeling approach which combines deterministic continuous [SBO:0000675] and discrete [SBO:0000295] simulation, where some participants are represented as deterministic, continuous variables and others are represented as discrete variables, without a detailed spatial representation of each participant. For example, a model may be simulated using a combination of a discrete simulation method such as Gillespie's algorithm and an ordinary differential equations integration method such as CVODE.
@graph.rdfs:label: hybrid deterministic continuous-discrete non-spatial framework

@graph.rdfs:comment: Modeling approach which combines stochastic continuous [SBO:0000676] and discrete [SBO:0000295] simulation, where some participants are represented as stochastic, continuous variables and others are represented as discrete variables, without a detailed spatial representation of each participant. For example, a model may be simulated using a combination of a discrete simulation method such as Gillespie's algorithm and an stochastic differential equations integration method.
@graph.rdfs:label: hybrid stochastic continuous-discrete non-spatial framework
